1
00:00:01,958 --> 00:00:05,125
[upbeat music plays]

2
00:00:05,208 --> 00:00:07,208
[singer] <i>♪ You never do know</i>
<i>what's around the bend ♪</i>

3
00:00:07,291 --> 00:00:09,375
<i>♪ Big adventure</i>
<i>or a brand-new friend ♪</i>

4
00:00:09,458 --> 00:00:11,125
<i>♪ When you're curious ♪</i>

5
00:00:11,208 --> 00:00:13,500
<i>-♪ Like Curious George ♪</i>
-[all] Swing!

6
00:00:13,583 --> 00:00:15,166
[singer]
<i>♪ Well, now, every day ♪</i>

7
00:00:15,250 --> 00:00:17,208
-[all]<i> ♪ Every day ♪</i>
-[singer] <i>♪ Is so glorious ♪</i>

8
00:00:17,291 --> 00:00:18,583
-[all] <i>♪ Glorious ♪</i>
-George.

9
00:00:18,666 --> 00:00:20,375
-[singer]<i> ♪ And everything ♪</i>
-[all] <i>♪ Everything ♪</i>

10
00:00:20,458 --> 00:00:22,583
-[singer] <i>♪ Is so wondrous ♪</i>
-[all] <i>♪ Wondrous ♪</i>

11
00:00:22,666 --> 00:00:24,375
[singer]
<i>♪ There's more to explore ♪</i>

12
00:00:24,458 --> 00:00:26,833
<i>♪ When you open your door ♪</i>

13
00:00:26,916 --> 00:00:28,541
<i>♪ And meet friends like this ♪</i>

14
00:00:28,625 --> 00:00:31,333
<i>-♪ You just can't miss ♪</i>
-[all] Whoa!

15
00:00:31,416 --> 00:00:33,458
-[singer] <i>♪ I get curious ♪</i>
-[all] <i>♪ Curious ♪</i>

16
00:00:33,541 --> 00:00:34,791
[singer]
<i>♪ And that's marvelous ♪</i>

17
00:00:34,875 --> 00:00:35,916
[all] <i>♪ Marvelous ♪</i>

18
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,166
[singer]
<i>♪ And that's your reward ♪</i>

19
00:00:38,250 --> 00:00:40,166
<i>♪ You'll never be bored ♪</i>

20
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:42,333
<i>♪ If you ask yourself,</i>
<i>"What is this?" ♪</i>

21
00:00:42,416 --> 00:00:44,333
<i>♪ Like Curious ♪</i>

22
00:00:44,416 --> 00:00:48,333
<i>♪ Like Curious,</i>
<i>Curious George ♪</i>

23
00:00:48,416 --> 00:00:49,250
Oh.

24
00:00:50,708 --> 00:00:53,625
[bright music plays]

25
00:00:53,708 --> 00:00:57,375
<i>♪♪</i>

26
00:00:57,458 --> 00:01:01,833
[narrator] <i>It was a perfect day</i>
<i>to enjoy the great outdoors.</i>

27
00:01:01,916 --> 00:01:04,375
[boxes dragging]

28
00:01:04,458 --> 00:01:05,750
[sighs]

29
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,750
[narrator] <i>But George was stuck</i>
<i>in the great indoors.</i>

30
00:01:08,833 --> 00:01:10,041
Some of this has been here

31
00:01:10,125 --> 00:01:12,208
since this was
my grandfather's house.

32
00:01:13,375 --> 00:01:15,291
-[grunts curiously]
-Uh…

33
00:01:15,375 --> 00:01:17,583
We should probably donate this.

34
00:01:17,666 --> 00:01:20,583
[gentle piano music plays]

35
00:01:20,666 --> 00:01:22,625
<i>♪♪</i>

36
00:01:22,708 --> 00:01:25,875
[chatters happily]

37
00:01:28,291 --> 00:01:29,125
[grunts curiously]

38
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:36,166
[chatters excitedly]

39
00:01:37,708 --> 00:01:39,250
Wow.

40
00:01:39,333 --> 00:01:42,333
This looks like one of my
Grandpa's Treasure Clue Maps.

41
00:01:42,416 --> 00:01:44,750
[chattering inquisitively]

42
00:01:44,833 --> 00:01:48,333
[laughs] Yeah, Grandpa
would hide clues

43
00:01:48,416 --> 00:01:50,458
and I'd follow them
to find the treasure.

44
00:01:50,541 --> 00:01:52,833
But I don't remember ever
seeing this one.

45
00:01:52,916 --> 00:01:55,708
[chattering happily]

46
00:01:55,791 --> 00:01:57,666
Okay, let's go.

47
00:01:57,750 --> 00:01:59,541
Let me grab my shovel
and compass!

48
00:01:59,625 --> 00:02:00,916
[chatters excitedly]

49
00:02:01,958 --> 00:02:05,708
[Man in the Yellow Hat] We're here!
Bugaboo Bend.

50
00:02:05,791 --> 00:02:09,708
[grunting happily]

51
00:02:09,791 --> 00:02:12,500
[laughs] Wait for me, George!

52
00:02:13,833 --> 00:02:16,500
Let's see…
according to the map,

53
00:02:16,583 --> 00:02:18,291
we need to dig up
the first clue

54
00:02:18,375 --> 00:02:19,666
here at the wishing well.

55
00:02:19,750 --> 00:02:22,583
X marks where we start.

56
00:02:22,666 --> 00:02:24,666
[grunting]

57
00:02:24,750 --> 00:02:27,750
[chatters inquisitively]

58
00:02:29,791 --> 00:02:32,500
[chatters questioningly]

59
00:02:32,583 --> 00:02:34,833
The X isn't on the ground,
George.

60
00:02:34,916 --> 00:02:37,708
-It's only on the map.
-[chatters curiously]

61
00:02:37,791 --> 00:02:40,375
The X shows that we should
dig by the well,

62
00:02:40,458 --> 00:02:42,875
and the N means
it's on the north side.

63
00:02:44,041 --> 00:02:46,416
[grunts]

64
00:02:46,500 --> 00:02:48,416
[grunting questioningly]

65
00:02:48,500 --> 00:02:51,041
The compass can show us
which side is north.

66
00:02:51,125 --> 00:02:52,250
[chatters]

67
00:02:52,333 --> 00:02:53,833
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
The N stands for north,

68
00:02:53,916 --> 00:02:56,750
and the needle
always points north.

69
00:02:56,833 --> 00:02:58,958
So we just need to line up

70
00:02:59,041 --> 00:03:02,041
the N with the needle
and then we walk north.

71
00:03:02,125 --> 00:03:03,750
[grunts]

72
00:03:03,833 --> 00:03:07,333
[cheerful music plays]

73
00:03:07,416 --> 00:03:09,000
[chatters happily]

74
00:03:09,083 --> 00:03:11,416
Yep, that's the north side.

75
00:03:11,500 --> 00:03:13,333
Let's hope it's here, George.

76
00:03:14,833 --> 00:03:16,625
[grunts]

77
00:03:16,708 --> 00:03:19,083
[chattering]

78
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:22,666
Ah

79
00:03:23,666 --> 00:03:26,083
[chattering curiously]

80
00:03:26,166 --> 00:03:29,666
[laughs] Don't worry, George.
That's not the treasure.

81
00:03:29,750 --> 00:03:32,500
It's just the first clue.
Open it.

82
00:03:34,791 --> 00:03:36,875
[chattering timidly]

83
00:03:36,958 --> 00:03:39,583
[chatters happily]

84
00:03:39,666 --> 00:03:43,500
"Head to the west
and find the mighty oak.

85
00:03:43,583 --> 00:03:47,041
Dig on its west side,
this is no joke."

86
00:03:48,958 --> 00:03:51,958
[narrator]
<i>But which way was west?</i>

87
00:03:52,041 --> 00:03:54,958
<i>The compass only had a needle</i>
<i>that pointed north.</i>

88
00:03:55,041 --> 00:03:57,375
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
The W stands for west.

89
00:03:57,458 --> 00:03:59,625
Once you line up
the compass with north,

90
00:03:59,708 --> 00:04:02,125
west is always to the left.

91
00:04:02,208 --> 00:04:03,833
Okay.

92
00:04:03,916 --> 00:04:07,583
[grunting excitedly]

93
00:04:10,041 --> 00:04:13,125
[distant train horn blares]

94
00:04:14,541 --> 00:04:16,750
[grunting happily]

95
00:04:16,833 --> 00:04:20,625
Hmm, we're supposed to find
the "mighty oak,"

96
00:04:20,708 --> 00:04:23,708
but oak trees don't have
white bark.

97
00:04:23,791 --> 00:04:25,875
These are birch trees, George.

98
00:04:25,958 --> 00:04:27,708
[grunts disappointingly]

99
00:04:27,791 --> 00:04:30,958
[sighs] There's a big ol' oak
here somewhere.

100
00:04:31,041 --> 00:04:33,416
[chuckles] Grandpa and I used
to climb it.

101
00:04:33,500 --> 00:04:37,000
It had a trunk this big.

102
00:04:37,083 --> 00:04:38,833
[chatters]

103
00:04:38,916 --> 00:04:40,833
[grunting]

104
00:04:40,916 --> 00:04:43,875
Yeah, like tha-- [gasps]
You're right!

105
00:04:43,958 --> 00:04:45,666
[chatters sheepishly]

106
00:04:45,750 --> 00:04:48,750
Ah, gee, I guess
they had to cut it down.

107
00:04:48,833 --> 00:04:51,666
Okay, let's find
the west side of it.

108
00:04:53,083 --> 00:04:55,708
[chatters curiously]

109
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,916
[grunts, giggles]

110
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
[chatters triumphantly]

111
00:05:04,083 --> 00:05:06,000
You did it, George!

112
00:05:11,916 --> 00:05:13,916
"Follow the tracks.

113
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:16,083
When you've reached
the same number of poles

114
00:05:16,166 --> 00:05:18,666
as you have hands,
dig to the south

115
00:05:18,750 --> 00:05:20,541
of where it stands."

116
00:05:20,625 --> 00:05:22,500
[grunts happily]

117
00:05:24,708 --> 00:05:27,958
[grunting excitedly]

118
00:05:31,791 --> 00:05:33,791
Hmm.

119
00:05:33,875 --> 00:05:35,875
That was pole number one.

120
00:05:35,958 --> 00:05:39,750
We need the same number
as you have hands.

121
00:05:39,833 --> 00:05:44,458
[grunting in succession]

122
00:05:44,541 --> 00:05:46,625
Four? [chuckles]

123
00:05:46,708 --> 00:05:49,000
Well, I guess monkeys
do have four hands,

124
00:05:49,083 --> 00:05:51,166
but these clues were written
for a little boy.

125
00:05:51,250 --> 00:05:52,958
[chuckles] Me.

126
00:05:53,041 --> 00:05:56,083
[chattering happily]

127
00:05:57,916 --> 00:06:00,166
[Man in the Yellow Hat] Right.

128
00:06:00,250 --> 00:06:03,083
[grunting happily]

129
00:06:03,166 --> 00:06:06,083
Now we "dig to the south."

130
00:06:06,166 --> 00:06:07,833
[chatters curiously]

131
00:06:07,916 --> 00:06:09,666
[Man in the Yellow Hat] See the S?

132
00:06:09,750 --> 00:06:11,500
That stands for south.

133
00:06:11,583 --> 00:06:13,625
South is the opposite of north.

134
00:06:13,708 --> 00:06:16,791
[grunting excitedly]

135
00:06:17,833 --> 00:06:21,208
[Man in the Yellow Hat grunting]

136
00:06:21,291 --> 00:06:24,833
[chattering happily]

137
00:06:26,958 --> 00:06:28,791
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
Here it goes.

138
00:06:28,875 --> 00:06:30,750
"Go directly east

139
00:06:30,833 --> 00:06:32,666
till you find a cider tree.

140
00:06:32,750 --> 00:06:35,791
The last clue is there
but it's kind of hard to see."

141
00:06:35,875 --> 00:06:38,291
-[gasps]
-[grunts curiously]

142
00:06:38,375 --> 00:06:42,625
Ooh, I'll bet cider tree
means apple, as in apple cider.

143
00:06:42,708 --> 00:06:44,791
[grunts]

144
00:06:44,875 --> 00:06:48,125
[chattering]

145
00:06:48,208 --> 00:06:49,958
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
You see the letter E?

146
00:06:50,041 --> 00:06:51,666
That's east.

147
00:06:51,750 --> 00:06:53,625
East is the opposite of west.

148
00:06:53,708 --> 00:06:55,291
That way!

149
00:06:55,375 --> 00:06:57,916
[chattering excitedly]

150
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,541
Wait, we need to refill
this hole.

151
00:07:01,625 --> 00:07:03,625
Uh, never mind.
You go.

152
00:07:03,708 --> 00:07:05,666
I'll catch up with you, okay?

153
00:07:05,750 --> 00:07:07,041
[chatters]

154
00:07:08,958 --> 00:07:10,791
Just make sure you keep
walking east

155
00:07:10,875 --> 00:07:12,291
until you come
to the first apple tree.

156
00:07:12,375 --> 00:07:13,916
[chatters]

157
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,125
[grunting happily]

158
00:07:16,208 --> 00:07:19,166
[bright music plays]

159
00:07:19,250 --> 00:07:25,833
<i>♪♪</i>

160
00:07:25,916 --> 00:07:27,833
[grunting]

161
00:07:27,916 --> 00:07:31,000
[giggles]

162
00:07:34,916 --> 00:07:37,208
[grunts]

163
00:07:44,833 --> 00:07:46,333
[chatters triumphantly]

164
00:07:47,708 --> 00:07:50,291
Excellent navigating, George.

165
00:07:50,375 --> 00:07:53,875
The clue says that once
we find the apple tree,

166
00:07:53,958 --> 00:07:56,750
"the last clue is hard to see."

167
00:07:56,833 --> 00:08:01,000
[chatters curiously]

168
00:08:01,083 --> 00:08:03,041
Good idea, George.

169
00:08:03,125 --> 00:08:06,208
Maybe Grandpa tied it
to a branch.

170
00:08:06,291 --> 00:08:08,250
[grunting happily]

171
00:08:09,708 --> 00:08:13,000
[chattering curiously]

172
00:08:13,083 --> 00:08:15,333
[grunting]

173
00:08:15,416 --> 00:08:17,791
[chattering happily]

174
00:08:17,875 --> 00:08:19,916
[squirrel chittering]

175
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,208
[shrieks, chitters]

176
00:08:23,291 --> 00:08:25,916
[chatters]

177
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,291
[chittering angrily]

178
00:08:28,375 --> 00:08:31,833
[grunting inquisitively]

179
00:08:33,791 --> 00:08:34,916
[chitters]

180
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,207
[chatters triumphantly]

181
00:08:38,291 --> 00:08:41,041
You found the last clue,
George.

182
00:08:41,125 --> 00:08:43,916
And a key?

183
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,375
"To find the treasure
and open the lock,

184
00:08:46,458 --> 00:08:49,916
walk ten steps
toward Turtle Rock."

185
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,083
Turtle Rock.

186
00:08:53,958 --> 00:08:55,708
[gasps, chatters]

187
00:08:55,791 --> 00:08:57,083
Yes, George?

188
00:08:57,166 --> 00:09:00,125
[grunting happily]

189
00:09:00,208 --> 00:09:02,833
That's it!
Ten steps.

190
00:09:02,916 --> 00:09:04,208
Ready?

191
00:09:04,291 --> 00:09:05,750
[grunts happily]

192
00:09:05,833 --> 00:09:08,416
-[grunting]
-One, two, three, four,

193
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:13,333
five, six, seven,
eight, nine, ten.

194
00:09:15,208 --> 00:09:17,875
Oh, I can't believe we're gonna
find Grandpa's treasure!

195
00:09:17,958 --> 00:09:20,208
[grunting]

196
00:09:21,375 --> 00:09:24,416
[grunting] Where is it?

197
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:27,208
I mean--it has to be here.

198
00:09:27,291 --> 00:09:30,083
[grunting sadly]

199
00:09:30,166 --> 00:09:31,916
Um…

200
00:09:33,833 --> 00:09:36,291
[sighs] It's not here.

201
00:09:36,375 --> 00:09:37,916
[grunts curiously]

202
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,041
Maybe Grandpa
never buried it.

203
00:09:40,125 --> 00:09:42,041
Or someone else found it.

204
00:09:42,125 --> 00:09:43,833
[grunts sadly]

205
00:09:43,916 --> 00:09:46,291
[sighs] Nothing to do now

206
00:09:46,375 --> 00:09:48,291
but fill in the hole
and go home.

207
00:09:48,375 --> 00:09:51,333
[chatters disappointingly]

208
00:09:54,833 --> 00:09:56,750
[sighs]

209
00:09:56,833 --> 00:09:58,458
[sighs]

210
00:10:01,291 --> 00:10:03,291
Hm? Oh.

211
00:10:03,375 --> 00:10:05,125
I'll slow down, George.

212
00:10:05,208 --> 00:10:09,291
I forget smaller legs
take smaller steps.

213
00:10:09,375 --> 00:10:11,250
[grunting]

214
00:10:11,333 --> 00:10:13,500
[narrator]
<i>His friend was right.</i>

215
00:10:13,583 --> 00:10:16,500
<i>Smaller legs did take</i>
<i>smaller steps.</i>

216
00:10:16,583 --> 00:10:18,333
[grunts triumphantly]

217
00:10:18,416 --> 00:10:21,375
[upbeat piano music plays]

218
00:10:21,458 --> 00:10:23,250
[chatters]

219
00:10:23,333 --> 00:10:25,125
Huh?

220
00:10:25,208 --> 00:10:28,958
[grunting in succession]

221
00:10:33,791 --> 00:10:36,166
[grunting excitedly]

222
00:10:36,250 --> 00:10:38,041
You think I should dig there?

223
00:10:38,125 --> 00:10:39,458
[chatters in agreement]

224
00:10:39,541 --> 00:10:40,958
Right.

225
00:10:42,083 --> 00:10:44,791
I went farther because
a grown-up's steps are longer.

226
00:10:44,875 --> 00:10:46,333
[grunting in agreement]

227
00:10:46,416 --> 00:10:49,083
And the treasure hunt wasn't
made for a grown-up!

228
00:10:49,166 --> 00:10:50,958
[laughs] Stand back!

229
00:10:51,041 --> 00:10:52,541
[grunts]
[thud]

230
00:10:52,625 --> 00:10:55,125
Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

231
00:10:56,625 --> 00:10:58,166
[grunts]

232
00:10:58,250 --> 00:10:59,958
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
Here it goes.

233
00:11:00,041 --> 00:11:01,875
Ready to see our treasure,
George?

234
00:11:01,958 --> 00:11:03,791
[grunts in agreement]

235
00:11:05,583 --> 00:11:07,166
[chatters inquisitively]

236
00:11:07,250 --> 00:11:09,375
[laughs] Pingle-tube!

237
00:11:09,458 --> 00:11:10,958
[grunts curiously]

238
00:11:11,041 --> 00:11:14,958
It's this great game
my Grandpa made up!

239
00:11:15,041 --> 00:11:18,208
"You solved the clues.
Your quest is done.

240
00:11:18,291 --> 00:11:21,291
The greatest treasure
is having fun!"

241
00:11:21,375 --> 00:11:23,958
[chuckles] "Love, Grandpa."

242
00:11:25,125 --> 00:11:26,833
[narrator] <i>George felt proud.</i>

243
00:11:26,916 --> 00:11:29,875
<i>He had found the lost treasure</i>
<i>of Bugaboo Bend.</i>

244
00:11:29,958 --> 00:11:31,500
[exciting banjo music plays]

245
00:11:31,583 --> 00:11:32,583
Go!

246
00:11:33,208 --> 00:11:35,000
[blows forcefully]

247
00:11:35,083 --> 00:11:37,458
-[laughs]
-[grunts]

248
00:11:37,541 --> 00:11:40,000
[narrator] <i>And got pretty good</i>
<i>at Pingle-tube too.</i>

249
00:11:40,083 --> 00:11:42,583
[laughing]

250
00:11:42,666 --> 00:11:44,250
[chatters curiously]

251
00:11:44,333 --> 00:11:47,333
[laughing]

252
00:11:49,666 --> 00:11:52,875
[laughter]

253
00:11:58,750 --> 00:12:01,666
[cheerful music plays]

254
00:12:01,750 --> 00:12:06,458
<i>♪♪</i>

255
00:12:07,291 --> 00:12:10,041
[narrator] <i>Lunch at Pisghetti's</i>
<i>was always fun,</i>

256
00:12:10,125 --> 00:12:12,416
<i>especially when there was</i>
<i>something to celebrate.</i>

257
00:12:12,500 --> 00:12:15,333
-[party horn honks]
-[giggles]

258
00:12:15,416 --> 00:12:19,625
Congratulations on winning
that essay contest.

259
00:12:19,708 --> 00:12:23,708
Well, I had a great topic:
George!

260
00:12:23,791 --> 00:12:25,541
[party horn honks]

261
00:12:26,291 --> 00:12:28,416
[party horn honks]

262
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:30,041
[gasps]

263
00:12:30,125 --> 00:12:34,625
Hey, a published author
deserves a special dessert!

264
00:12:34,708 --> 00:12:38,041
Chef's famous apple pie!

265
00:12:38,125 --> 00:12:42,000
Oh, apple pie!
My favorite!

266
00:12:42,083 --> 00:12:46,541
This is the last piece,
so you two will have to share.

267
00:12:46,625 --> 00:12:50,333
Tell me, how did you do it?

268
00:12:52,083 --> 00:12:54,208
[Man in the Yellow Hat]
Well, you see, I find

269
00:12:54,291 --> 00:12:58,208
that writing just requires
the right inspiration,

270
00:12:58,291 --> 00:13:03,041
and well, for me,
that inspiration is George.

271
00:13:03,125 --> 00:13:05,333
[chatters questioningly]

272
00:13:05,416 --> 00:13:09,625
Georgio, that piece was
to share with your friend.

273
00:13:09,708 --> 00:13:13,666
[chattering apologetically]

274
00:13:15,125 --> 00:13:18,000
Oh, it's okay.
I'll get some next time.

275
00:13:18,083 --> 00:13:20,333
You know,
I've always wanted to try

276
00:13:20,416 --> 00:13:22,333
-writing poetry.
-Oh?

277
00:13:22,416 --> 00:13:24,458
[narrator]
<i>George thought there must be</i>

278
00:13:24,541 --> 00:13:26,458
<i>more pie in the kitchen.</i>

279
00:13:26,541 --> 00:13:30,250
[mellow music plays]

280
00:13:30,333 --> 00:13:33,291
[grunting curiously]

281
00:13:33,375 --> 00:13:35,333
[grunting inquisitively]

282
00:13:35,416 --> 00:13:39,416
Oh, sorry, Georgio, we're out
of my <i>delizioso </i>pie,

283
00:13:39,500 --> 00:13:43,083
and I'm much too busy
to make more.

284
00:13:43,166 --> 00:13:44,458
[chatters sadly]

285
00:13:44,541 --> 00:13:47,125
[grunting thoughtfully]

286
00:13:47,208 --> 00:13:49,541
[narrator] <i>George wondered</i>
<i>if he could make the pie.</i>

287
00:13:49,625 --> 00:13:54,208
<i>It was just apple goo</i>
<i>and yummy crust.</i>

288
00:13:54,291 --> 00:13:56,791
[chattering]

289
00:13:56,875 --> 00:13:59,291
[chattering excitedly]

290
00:13:59,375 --> 00:14:03,458
Wha--you want to make my pie,
Georgio?

291
00:14:03,541 --> 00:14:05,625
[grunting in agreement]

292
00:14:05,708 --> 00:14:09,708
Well, my famous pie
is very easy to make.

293
00:14:09,791 --> 00:14:12,625
Okay, I'll give you the recipe.

294
00:14:12,708 --> 00:14:14,625
[chatters questioningly]

295
00:14:14,708 --> 00:14:18,666
Well, a recipe tells you how
to make pie or other foods.

296
00:14:18,750 --> 00:14:22,125
For you, I'm gonna write it
in pictures.

297
00:14:22,208 --> 00:14:24,833
[peppy music plays]

298
00:14:24,916 --> 00:14:27,833
These steps are
for the apple filling.

299
00:14:27,916 --> 00:14:30,250
Wash six apples,

300
00:14:30,333 --> 00:14:32,833
then add 1/2 cup of sugar--

301
00:14:32,916 --> 00:14:35,791
that means cup is filled
to the middle, eh--

302
00:14:35,875 --> 00:14:38,833
then a teaspoon of cinnamon.

303
00:14:38,916 --> 00:14:41,833
Next, add a little lemon,

304
00:14:41,916 --> 00:14:44,291
mix it all up.
Voila!

305
00:14:44,375 --> 00:14:46,166
<i>Molto bene!</i>

306
00:14:46,250 --> 00:14:48,083
[grunts affirmatively]

307
00:14:48,166 --> 00:14:52,666
Now the steps for
my <i>fantastico </i>flaky crust.

308
00:14:52,750 --> 00:14:57,250
The oven gets set
to 350 degrees.

309
00:14:57,333 --> 00:14:59,541
But, Georgio,

310
00:14:59,625 --> 00:15:02,666
you got to get an adult
to help you set the oven.

311
00:15:02,750 --> 00:15:04,458
[chatters affirmatively]

312
00:15:04,541 --> 00:15:07,125
Take 1 teaspoon of salt,

313
00:15:07,208 --> 00:15:09,166
2 cups of flour,

314
00:15:09,250 --> 00:15:11,750
a stick of butter,

315
00:15:11,833 --> 00:15:14,750
and 1 cup of water.

316
00:15:14,833 --> 00:15:17,375
Put them in a bowl.

317
00:15:17,458 --> 00:15:20,250
We're going to mix
them all up,

318
00:15:20,333 --> 00:15:22,375
-flatten it out…
-[grunts]

319
00:15:22,458 --> 00:15:24,583
Then lay it in a pie pan,

320
00:15:24,666 --> 00:15:26,500
add the apple filling,

321
00:15:26,583 --> 00:15:29,458
and bake for 45 minutes.

322
00:15:29,541 --> 00:15:31,208
Voila!

323
00:15:31,291 --> 00:15:34,125
[grunting, mimics]

324
00:15:35,458 --> 00:15:38,125
[narrator] <i>George was ready</i>
<i>to make a pie.</i>

325
00:15:41,625 --> 00:15:44,250
Maybe I'll get some dessert.

326
00:15:44,333 --> 00:15:46,875
[grunting]

327
00:15:46,958 --> 00:15:49,750
Oh, you want to get me
dessert?

328
00:15:49,833 --> 00:15:51,625
[chatters affirmatively]

329
00:15:51,708 --> 00:15:55,916
Okay, just, uh,
keep it simple.

330
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,791
I'll be in my room writing…
a poem.

331
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:02,833
[sighs] I should think
of a rhyme for monkey.

332
00:16:02,916 --> 00:16:04,291
Funky?

333
00:16:04,375 --> 00:16:05,833
Chunky.

334
00:16:05,916 --> 00:16:08,500
[bright music plays]

335
00:16:08,583 --> 00:16:10,583
[narrator] <i>George started</i>
<i>with the apple filling.</i>

336
00:16:10,666 --> 00:16:14,208
<i>First step, wash six apples.</i>

337
00:16:14,291 --> 00:16:17,875
<i>♪♪</i>

338
00:16:17,958 --> 00:16:19,208
[chatters]

339
00:16:19,291 --> 00:16:24,375
[narrator] <i>One, two, three,</i>
<i>four, five, six.</i>

340
00:16:25,541 --> 00:16:26,958
-[grunting]
-[narrator] <i>The dishwasher</i>

341
00:16:27,041 --> 00:16:29,291
<i>got things really clean.</i>

342
00:16:29,375 --> 00:16:33,291
[grunting]

343
00:16:34,958 --> 00:16:36,416
[bottle squirts]

344
00:16:36,500 --> 00:16:39,416
[narrator]
<i>Six apples, six squirts.</i>

345
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:43,208
[grunting]

346
00:16:43,916 --> 00:16:45,958
[beep]

347
00:16:46,041 --> 00:16:47,916
-[dishwasher whirring]
-[grunts]

348
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:50,500
[narrator] <i>Now to collect</i>
<i>the other ingredients.</i>

349
00:16:50,583 --> 00:16:51,791
[chatters]

350
00:16:51,875 --> 00:16:53,875
[narrator] <i>He needed sugar…</i>

351
00:16:56,458 --> 00:16:58,375
<i>And cinnamon.</i>

352
00:16:59,791 --> 00:17:02,666
[sniffing, grunts in disgust]

353
00:17:02,750 --> 00:17:05,290
[sniffs, sighs]

354
00:17:06,415 --> 00:17:08,540
[narrator] <i>And lemon.</i>

355
00:17:08,625 --> 00:17:12,290
Living with a monkey
is humbling.

356
00:17:12,375 --> 00:17:14,833
-[rumbling]
-What's that rumbling?

357
00:17:14,915 --> 00:17:17,250
[laughs] That rhymes!

358
00:17:17,333 --> 00:17:21,665
[chattering]

359
00:17:21,750 --> 00:17:24,000
Oh, it's a surprise.

360
00:17:24,083 --> 00:17:25,665
Sorry, George.

361
00:17:25,750 --> 00:17:27,583
[beeping]

362
00:17:29,583 --> 00:17:32,916
[grunting]

363
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:35,750
[steam hisses]

364
00:17:35,833 --> 00:17:38,333
[grunting happily]

365
00:17:38,416 --> 00:17:39,458
[narrator]
<i>Apples in apple pie</i>

366
00:17:39,541 --> 00:17:41,958
<i>were supposed to be</i>
<i>nice and gooey.</i>

367
00:17:42,041 --> 00:17:44,916
[splattering]

368
00:17:46,958 --> 00:17:50,375
<i>Next, he needed a cup filled</i>
<i>to the middle with sugar.</i>

369
00:17:50,458 --> 00:17:55,291
<i>♪♪</i>

370
00:17:55,375 --> 00:17:57,708
<i>Sugar cubes were fun.</i>

371
00:17:57,791 --> 00:17:59,875
[grunts curiously]

372
00:17:59,958 --> 00:18:03,041
[narrator]
<i>But he had too many.</i>

373
00:18:03,125 --> 00:18:05,375
<i>Just half a cup.</i>

374
00:18:05,458 --> 00:18:07,791
<i>Next a spoonful of lemon.</i>

375
00:18:11,625 --> 00:18:12,833
[chatters happily]

376
00:18:14,583 --> 00:18:16,791
[narrator]
<i>And a spoonful of cinnamon.</i>

377
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:20,500
[grunting happily]

378
00:18:26,416 --> 00:18:28,416
[triumphant music plays]

379
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:29,583
[chatters]

380
00:18:29,666 --> 00:18:31,041
[narrator]
<i>Time to make the crust.</i>

381
00:18:32,791 --> 00:18:34,625
[grunts thoughtfully]

382
00:18:34,708 --> 00:18:37,333
[narrator] <i>He needed an adult</i>
<i>to turn on the oven</i>

383
00:18:37,416 --> 00:18:39,625
[grunts enthusiastically]

384
00:18:41,541 --> 00:18:44,750
Mmm, smells like cinnamon
in here.

385
00:18:44,833 --> 00:18:47,375
[shushes]

386
00:18:47,458 --> 00:18:50,875
[softly] Oh, you doing
something secret, George?

387
00:18:50,958 --> 00:18:52,708
[chattering affirmatively]

388
00:18:55,458 --> 00:18:58,666
[whispering]
Your secret's safe with me.

389
00:19:01,833 --> 00:19:03,791
[narrator] <i>It was time</i>
<i>to gather the ingredients</i>

390
00:19:03,875 --> 00:19:05,916
<i>for the crust.</i>

391
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,875
<i>First, a spoonful of salt.</i>

392
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:17,416
[grunting]

393
00:19:19,041 --> 00:19:20,750
[chatters happily]

394
00:19:20,833 --> 00:19:24,791
[narrator]
<i>Then 2 full cups of flour.</i>

395
00:19:29,875 --> 00:19:31,125
[chatters]

396
00:19:31,208 --> 00:19:34,541
[narrator]
<i>Next, add the butter.</i>

397
00:19:35,916 --> 00:19:39,666
[chattering happily]

398
00:19:39,750 --> 00:19:41,750
[narrator]
<i>And a cup of water.</i>

399
00:19:47,125 --> 00:19:48,750
<i>Mixing time.</i>

400
00:19:48,833 --> 00:19:50,791
<i>George remembered this part.</i>

401
00:19:50,875 --> 00:19:53,916
[grunting excitedly]

402
00:19:55,583 --> 00:19:58,166
[narrator]
<i>Next, make the dough flat.</i>

403
00:20:03,500 --> 00:20:06,625
[musical drum flourish]

404
00:20:06,708 --> 00:20:09,416
[grunting happily]

405
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:10,916
[narrator]
<i>Now George needed</i>

406
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:12,958
<i>a round pan to put it in.</i>

407
00:20:13,041 --> 00:20:14,541
[pans clattering]

408
00:20:14,625 --> 00:20:16,583
[chatters triumphantly]

409
00:20:16,666 --> 00:20:19,666
[gentle music plays]

410
00:20:19,750 --> 00:20:21,791
[grunts thoughtfully]

411
00:20:21,875 --> 00:20:25,416
[narrator] <i>Maybe crust would</i>
<i>shrink in the oven.</i>

412
00:20:27,208 --> 00:20:29,500
[chatters curiously]

413
00:20:29,583 --> 00:20:31,916
[grunting]

414
00:20:33,625 --> 00:20:35,208
[chatters triumphantly]

415
00:20:35,291 --> 00:20:37,666
[narrator]
<i>It was baking time.</i>

416
00:20:41,291 --> 00:20:43,791
[dramatic music plays]

417
00:20:43,875 --> 00:20:47,875
Boy, you creative types
sure are messy.

418
00:20:47,958 --> 00:20:50,166
[shushes, chatters]

419
00:20:50,250 --> 00:20:53,083
[chattering happily]

420
00:20:53,166 --> 00:20:58,000
Gee, I guess I just don't get
gourmet cooking.

421
00:20:59,916 --> 00:21:03,958
[narrator] <i>George's recipe</i>
<i>said to bake the pie for 45.</i>

422
00:21:06,500 --> 00:21:08,833
[timer beeping]

423
00:21:10,958 --> 00:21:12,708
[grunts]

424
00:21:12,791 --> 00:21:14,583
[chatters thankfully]

425
00:21:14,666 --> 00:21:16,250
[whispers] Anytime.

426
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:19,833
George, could--could I get
a glass of water?

427
00:21:19,916 --> 00:21:22,666
-Here you go.
-Thanks!

428
00:21:24,833 --> 00:21:27,125
George, what was the doorman--

429
00:21:27,208 --> 00:21:28,833
[gasps]

430
00:21:31,625 --> 00:21:33,875
Well, you didn't keep it simple.

431
00:21:33,958 --> 00:21:35,791
[timer beeping]

432
00:21:37,208 --> 00:21:40,958
[grunting excitedly]

433
00:21:42,333 --> 00:21:44,666
[chatters triumphantly]

434
00:21:44,750 --> 00:21:46,875
Huh, you made me a…

435
00:21:46,958 --> 00:21:50,208
a-- What is that?

436
00:21:50,291 --> 00:21:52,583
[chattering happily]

437
00:21:54,166 --> 00:21:56,291
[grunting]

438
00:21:58,875 --> 00:22:00,625
You made me an apple pie?

439
00:22:00,708 --> 00:22:04,208
[chatters in agreement]

440
00:22:10,375 --> 00:22:12,583
Oh, my.
[laughs awkwardly]

441
00:22:12,666 --> 00:22:17,083
It's really salty
and cinnamon-y. [chuckles]

442
00:22:19,291 --> 00:22:23,791
[grunting in disgust]

443
00:22:23,875 --> 00:22:26,250
[chattering questioningly]

444
00:22:26,333 --> 00:22:29,541
Well, George, it looks like
things didn't go

445
00:22:29,625 --> 00:22:31,125
quite as planned.

446
00:22:31,208 --> 00:22:34,041
[grunting sadly]

447
00:22:34,125 --> 00:22:36,208
Hey, how about
after we clean this up,

448
00:22:36,291 --> 00:22:39,833
we get more ingredients
and make a pie together?

449
00:22:39,916 --> 00:22:44,166
-[chatters enthusiastically]
-Wait, that's it!

450
00:22:44,250 --> 00:22:46,958
I once tried to rhyme
with a monkey,

451
00:22:47,041 --> 00:22:49,875
and my rhyming was
all very clunky.

452
00:22:49,958 --> 00:22:53,291
Then George made a pie.
He gave it a try.

453
00:22:53,375 --> 00:22:56,333
Together,
we'll make one less…

454
00:22:56,416 --> 00:22:58,000
chunky?

455
00:22:58,083 --> 00:22:59,750
[chattering happily]

456
00:22:59,833 --> 00:23:02,291
[giggling]

457
00:23:03,375 --> 00:23:06,333
[upbeat music plays]

458
00:23:06,416 --> 00:23:13,416
<i>♪♪</i>

